Okay, so enough about my capability. Now onto my experience.

I can remember at nine-years-old sitting in church criticizing really bad social engineering. In this case a couple was getting married. Our preacher went into how serious marriage commitment was and to not take it lightly because there are over seven-hundred rights and privileges in State and Federal law assigned to marriage. At nine-years old I said to myself, "That's stupid. Everyone should be allowed to assign those seven-hundred rights individually as we see fit." The point here is not that is the correct view of marriage rights, but rather I was already social engineering at the age of nine.

My social engineering interest and efforts really took off in 1980 when I graduated from high school and Raygun Reagan became President.

The first thread I pulled for social engineering was American Revolution history. I was fascinated with Benjamin Franklin, John Adams, George Washington, Thomas Paine, James Madison, and Alexander Hamilton. As far as I know this was a unique point in time where so many brilliant people collaborated. I started reading their biographies as well as history of the Revolutionary War and subsequent Constitution creation.

I also started psychology and self-help books in order to manage my neurodivergent maladies. Sadly, in 1980 there was no Autism community with books on neurodivergent management practices. So I was limited to neurotypical help. Turns out that that sleep and physical exercise regimemes for neurotypicals were very helpful for myself.

I started community college in 1987 and took classes on modern anthropology, politics among other social engineering necessities.

Eventually in the 1990s I added consuming day-to-day political news and commentary to my education.

My qualifications are a high scholastic aptitude and a specialty of generality. Further I've educated myself for decades by reading on social engineering topics since 1980.

Politically I'm left of left of left. When you think about it this has to be the case. Conservatives are focused on preserving the past. Anyone focused on wholesale replacement of current society has to be liberal. I do not expect many conservatives to engage with New Democracy.
